==Marriage and descendants==
In 1206, he married  his fourth cousin Infanta [[Urraca of Castile, Queen of Portugal|Urraca of Castile]], daughter of [[Alfonso VIII of Castile]] and [[Eleanor of England, Queen of Castile|Eleanor of England]], both being descendants of King [[Alfonso VI of León]].{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=99 and 101}} The offspring of this marriage were:

* [[Sancho II of Portugal|Infante Sancho]] (8 September 1207{{snd}}4 January 1248), succeeded his father as Sancho II, 4th [[King of Portugal]];{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=102}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=167}} 
* [[Afonso III of Portugal|Infante Afonso]] (5 May 1210{{snd}}16 February 1279), succeeded his brother Sancho as Afonso III, 5th [[King of Portugal]];{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=102}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=167-168}}
* [[Leonor of Portugal, Queen of Denmark|Infanta Leonor]] (Eleanor) (1211–1231). Married [[Valdemar the Young]],{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=102 and 210}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=167}} son of [[Valdemar II of Denmark]] and Margaret of Bohemia, daughter of [[Ottokar I of Bohemia]];
* [[Fernando, Lord of Serpa|Infante Fernando]] (1218–1246),{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=102 and 110}}  Lord of [[Serpa]] and married to Sancha Fernández de Lara with whom he had no issue. He was the father of an illegitimate son, Sancho Fernandes, prior of Santo Estêvão of Alfama.{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=167}}

Out of wedlock, he had two illegitimate sons:
* João Afonso (d. 9 October 1234), buried in the Alcobaça monastery;{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=168}}
* Pedro Afonso (d. after 1249). Accompanied his brother King Afonso in the conquest of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]] in 1249. He had an illegitimate daughter named Constança Peres. {{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=168}}

